The places of infection have not changed significantly, with people mostly getting infected within their families, but there are also other places of infection, which have led to certain restrictions and limitations being imposed by the Government of the Republic.
Our main concern continues to be the number of cases where we do not know the source of infection, which was thirty-four percent last week, indicating that we still have a high risk of infection and the disease can come from anywhere.
We continue to register imported cases, but fortunately, the number has been decreasing over the weeks, with sixty-one cases last week, mostly coming from Russia, Finland, and Sweden.
In terms of age structure, as new cases are coming in strongly, they are present in all age groups.
Last week, most of the new cases were in the age groups of sixty to sixty-nine (seventeen percent), fifty to fifty-nine (thirteen percent), and forty to forty-nine (twelve percent). A positive moment is that last week, the number of cases in the ninety plus age group decreased by a quarter.
We know that Covid-19 can manifest with symptoms or without, and last week, ten percent of the cases were asymptomatic, and one hundred and eighty-seven people needed hospitalization.
It is very important to note that almost eighty percent of those hospitalized were over the age of sixty, which indicates that the disease is worsening and the course of the disease will be more serious for older people.
We continue to be concerned about the care institutions, which are still the most vulnerable risk areas, and we have conducted a small analysis comparing the fourteen-day incidence per one hundred thousand inhabitants in both care homes and the general population. Among clients aged sixty and above in care homes, the risk of infection is almost seven times higher.

Once again, if the disease enters care homes, it is a serious problem. And of course, we continue to emphasize that our healthcare system is currently under a very heavy burden and we must do everything to ensure that all people who need hospital treatment, not just those with Covid-19, but also those with other concerns, receive the necessary care.

A few words about the incidence in Harju County. As of today, the fourteen-day incidence per one hundred thousand inhabitants is five hundred and eighty-eight point eighty-two. In Tallinn, the number is five hundred and ninety, in the town of Loksa one thousand three hundred and thirty-eight, and in the town of Maardu seven hundred and fifty-one. But let's compare this to Ida-Viru County, where the indicator is one thousand and fifty-three, making it our biggest concern at the moment.

In Harju County, there are currently over seventeen thousand people under active surveillance, of which fourteen thousand are close contacts and over three thousand are active cases. Today, we have twenty-four active outbreaks, mostly in workplaces, family clusters, but also in care homes.

And now, what should we do next, how should we behave? Figuratively speaking, in order to overcome this crisis, everything is very simple and clear - all those who are sick must calmly stay at home and recover. And during the time when they are infectious, their contacts should be kept to a minimum, so that we can get rid of the virus.

This is an ideal world that we are striving towards, but it is probably not achievable one hundred percent. Nevertheless, we must all contribute together to not spread the virus and help those who need assistance.

And what do we need to continue doing? We must adhere to the measures imposed by the government, maintain distance, wear masks, reduce contacts, and avoid crowded places and events.
We will skip big parties this time and celebrate Christmas mostly at home with our immediate family and the people we interact with on a daily basis.
And we will stay at home as much as possible and enjoy the beautiful nature of Estonia to reduce the risk of getting infected and not pass on the infection to our family members. I wish everyone a Merry Christmas and let's stay healthy, thank you.
